And as to the Hebrew word Guolam, the critick abovenamed ſays it deſigns "abſolute perpetuity, eternity;" when it affirms of God, or things in their own nature eternal; and it will be ſtill further proved in the ſequel, that future puniſhment is ſo. The abovenamed Reply obſerves that the import of thoſe words is meaſured by the ſubject to which they apply; 
                     •
                  f to the Jewiſh ſtate of the church, or its ordinances; the mountains, &c. The durability imported in theſe words is equal to that of their ſubject. So when they apply to God, his gracious covenant, or the future ſtate of exiſtence, they import duration equal to their ſubject. And it has been proved by plain texts, that the above Greek word often neceſſarily means eternity. Therefore the ſchoolmen ſay, that wicked men are juſtly puniſhed in eterno Dei, who have ſinned in eterno Deo. i. e. They ſhall be puniſhed through eternity, as meaſured by God, who have ſinned through their whole life here. And this Hebrew word certainly means eternity in the moſt abſolute ſenſe in Pſalm x. 16. "The Lord is king for ever and ever." And in Exod. xv. 18. "The Lord ſhall reign for ever and ever." Beſides,
